---
import BaseLayout from '../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import SiteHeader from '../components/SiteHeader.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Colm Murphy | Process Design"
  description="Colm Murphy's product design process across research, testing, accessibility, delivery, and design team collaboration."
  image="/src/img/ProcessDesign/ProcessBanner.webp"
  imageAlt="Illustration representing Colm Murphy's product design process"
>
  <SiteHeader gradient="ProcessGradient" />

  <main class="m-auto font-light text-slate-600 leading-loose">
    <section class="sectionFrame relative ProcessGradient overflow-clip group">
      <img
        class="absolute opacity-10 transition-transform duration-500 ease-in-out group-hover:scale-110 group-hover:blur-sm"
        src="/src/img/ProcessDesign/ProcessBanner.webp"
        alt="Abstract background for the process design page"
        fetchpriority="high"
      />

      <div class="sectionDiv grid grid-cols-1 sm:grid-cols-2 gap-4 items-center">
        <div class="w-full z-10">
          <h1 class="mb-6 font-bold text-xl sm:text-4xl text-white">UX &amp; Product Design</h1>
          <hr class="horizontalRule bg-amber-500" />
          <p class="text-slate-100">Notes on tools and process.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="hidden sm:block ml-auto z-10">
          <img src="/src/img/ProcessDesign/tooling.svg" alt="Illustration of product design tooling" />
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sectionFrameOn relative">
      <div class="sectionDiv">
        <div class="space-y-6 z-10">
          <h2 class="paragraphHeading">Design Philosophy</h2>
          <hr class="horizontalRule PDhorizontalRuleColour" />
          <p>
            UX &amp; Product Design is simply about best serving the needs of current users,
            building the needs of future users, predicting trends and avoiding churn.
            There are a lot of ways to set up design teams to achieve this.
          </p>
          <p>
            Product design is a discipline with key markers and outcomes. As a product designer I expect myself and others
            to discover and address problems and then exit leaving behind change.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sectionFrameOnAlt">
      <div class="sectionDiv">
        <div class="space-y-6 z-10">
          <h2 class="paragraphHeading">Research &amp; Discovery</h2>
          <hr class="horizontalRule PDhorizontalRuleColour" />
          <p>
            If you do not know what and who you are building for, the leanest scrum or the most agile
            project will not help you. I like to test to the point of routine.
          </p>
          <p>
            I prefer to record interviews and use Dovetail to analyze sentiment afterwards.
            This keeps me in the moment during the interview instead of taking notes.
          </p>
          <p>
            Insights and stories can be produced from this so there can be no debate as to what was
            discussed. I am not interested in a battle of opinions about what was implied.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sectionFrameOn">
      <div class="sectionDiv">
        <div class="space-y-6 z-10">
          <h2 class="paragraphHeading">Testing, Testing &amp; Testing</h2>
          <hr class="horizontalRule PDhorizontalRuleColour" />
          <p>
            I also like to validate to the point of routine. I feel that the work UX teams can do in
            advance, makes dev sprint cycles easier and eventually reduces pressure on support teams.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sectionFrameOnAlt">
      <div class="sectionDiv">
        <div class="space-y-6 z-10">
          <h2 class="paragraphHeading">Team Design</h2>
          <hr class="horizontalRule PDhorizontalRuleColour" />
          <p>
            I have found that team structure makes a dramatic difference to whatever process is in place.
            Designers, ideally with QA and product, at the root of teams makes it a smoother cycle.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sectionFrameOn">
      <div class="sectionDiv">
        <div class="space-y-6 z-10">
          <h2 class="paragraphHeading">Design Thinking and Business Impact</h2>
          <hr class="horizontalRule PDhorizontalRuleColour" />
          <p>
            Places like IBM and others have designers at the O level of the business. I think the trend will
            go that way with designers holding more influence. For me personally, I like to consider all areas of a
            business within my reach. I do not mean that I wish them to do what I want, though.
          </p>
          <p>
            For example, I want to know the issues support teams are having. If 15% of their time is spent
            on "how do I do this", that is something a UXer can help with through research and interviews.
            If we can reduce this to 5% month on month then we are improving product scores as well
            as reducing the cost to serve the product.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <section class="sectionFrameOnAlt">
      <div class="sectionDiv">
        <div class="space-y-6 z-10">
          <h2 class="paragraphHeading">More Testing</h2>
          <hr class="horizontalRule PDhorizontalRuleColour" />
          <p>
            Sorry, but I cannot stress it enough. Ideally you include users in the process so the expectation is
            that they will test the product. This includes tools like maze which take your direct wireframes and record
            flows, correct and incorrect clicks, click rates, bounce rates and more. It is important to me to never feel
            like I know better, because I do not.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <div class="px-6 py-32 grid place-items-center">
      <a href="mailto:colmmurchu@gmail.com?subject=Hello friend!" aria-label="Email Colm Murphy">
        <svg class="mailTo text-white fill-current h-10 w-10 rounded-full" viewBox="0 0 36 36" aria-hidden="true">
          <path d="M10,10H10c-1.1,0-1.99,0.9-1.99,2L8,24c0,1.1,0.9,2,2,2h16c1.1,0,2-0.9,2-2V12C28,10.9,27.1,10,26,10z M10,24H10V14l8,5l8-5V24z M18,17l-8-5h16L18,17z" />
        </svg>
      </a>
    </div>
  </main>
</BaseLayout>